###Converting $\theta$ to degrees 

Using the formula, we get the following conversion. 

$\begin{align}\text{Angle in Degrees} &= \dfrac{180^\circ}{\pi}\cdot\text{Angle in Radians}
\\\\ &= \dfrac{180^\circ}{\pi}\cdot\dfrac{257\pi}{360}
\\\\&=128.5^\circ\end{align}$

options.explanation:
Trigonometric values for $0^\circ$:

$\begin{align}\sin (0^\circ)&=0
\\\\\cos (0^\circ)&=1  \end{align}$ 


Trigonometric values for $30^\circ$:

$\begin{align}\sin (30^\circ)&=\dfrac{1}{2}
\\\\\cos (30^\circ)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} 
 \end{align}$ 

Trigonometric values for $45^\circ$: 

$\begin{align}\sin (45^\circ)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
\\\\\cos (45^\circ)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{align}$ 

Trigonometric values for $60^\circ$: 

$\begin{align}\sin (60^\circ)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\\\\\cos (60^\circ)&=\dfrac{1}{2} \end{align}$

Trigonometric values for $0$:

$\begin{align}\sin (0)&=0
\\\\\cos (0)&=1  \end{align}$ 

Trigonometric values for $\dfrac{\pi}{6}$:

$\begin{align} \sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right) &=\dfrac{1}{2}
\\\\\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} 
 \end{align}$ 

Trigonometric values for $\dfrac{\pi}{4}$: 

$\begin{align}\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
\\\\\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{align}$ 

Trigonometric values for $\dfrac{\pi}{3}$: 

$\begin{align}\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)&=\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
\\\\\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi}{3}\right)&=\dfrac{1}{2} \end{align}$

